<HR size="1" color="#dedfdf">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Greetings,<P>I am glad that at least someone managed to catch Alan's ear with something that brought this topic to the forefront. Personally, I was just shocked it was me   <IMG SRC="wink.gif" border="0"> Anyways, I sat down after seeing this and wrote up a reply to Alan's comments. I did miss something, however, and it partly has to do with the concept of "drastically improving" my soloability. In the tactic within my reply that I pointed out, I failed to acknowledge that in fact my soloability had actually improved in circumventing the penalty. Half of this is simply gaining more experience over time. This in itself doesn't "improve my soloability" as the creatures I can solo still remain the same as before. What permitted me to improve how many I could solo at once before requiring meditation was oddly part tactic, and part my equipment (ie: my Burnt Wood Staff). Without that little trinket, my soloability circumventing the experience penalty would be about on par with the other tactics.<P>Anyways, here's my reply... Alan's comments are in bold, mine are not.<P>  <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR><BR><B>I wanted to talk a bit about the idea of pets taking experience in groups. I'm talking as Alan at this point, not so much so as a member of the EverQuest team, so I'll be presenting my own arguments. I'd like to hear comments about what I have to say.<BR>Obviously several players of pet classes have sent me comments about the idea that pets can take experience. A sample would be:<P>"Followup) Right here, we have a break in vision between design and practice. These two questions are lumped together in order to discuss them both at once. For myself, a level 56 Magician, it is trivial for me to evade this 50% penalty for the pet's "hard work" by simply destroying my pet, wasting 1 malachite, and finishing the mob off myself while it runs. This has not drastically improved my soloing ability. What it has done is permitted me to consider 'light blue' mobs as viable targets for experience, just like every other class in Norrath can do. With my pet chewing up half my experience for light blue, I must either outdamage my pet via spells (costly), chain cast pets (costly in Malachite), or simply to not use my pets up until the finishing blow.<P>As for a pet ever taking experience in a group, this concept reeks of the same problems socially as the Hybrid experience penalties did. Exactally what reason would a group have for selecting a Magician over a rogue, monk, other melee, wizard, or any other class that would not suck experience away from the group as a whole? Because it makes it easier to fight? It can be said that a well balanced group will be able to outdamage a pet. However, consider that higher in levels, and at it's peak the Epic Pet, these pets become harder to outdamage if they're used properly. It would simply break my heart to hear "Get the fire pet out, it doesn't do as much damage as your rogue pet". By stating and verifying that This Is So for experience penalties, you condem all Pet classes to go Petless, something that at least for Magicians and Beastlords would go against their very design.<P>Rhasin Firestorm"<P>I cut this out of your response, Rhasin. I'm sorry about not posting the whole thing, but I wanted to focus on this particular issue.</B><P>That's ok   <IMG SRC="smile.gif" border="0"> To be honest, it caught me by suprise to have been representative of the current influx of posts following the Q/A list. Hopefully, the remainder of the points, or even the questions post in there will be considered and/or clarified at a later date (though at least on some, I was seeking confirmation to observations).<P><B>Your first paragraph talks about how some folks find it better to work around the experience issue by various methods. While we really don't want to create game mechanics that players find a desire to 'work around' there is some value to this. First, since this is part is about soloing, even with the potential experience loss, mages are not the worst at soloing. So it could easily be argued that removing this penalty from soloing pet casters would simply improve them as soloers, something they already do fairly well.<P>But folks using work around methods are, basically, being less efficient when it comes to use of mana. Recasting pets and nuking to do more damage than the pet are mana expensive techniques when compared to keeping one buffed up pet and letting it do most of the work. This means more work for the pet caster and more downtime for more experience. While I'm certainly not going try to convince you that work arounds are good things, these seem to be balanced with the way things work. More effort, more time, more experience (no greater risk).</B><P>Actually, in my particular case, for me to ditch my pet at the end of a fight is actually LESS mana intensive. For my particular case, I present the following tactics:<P>1) I can use my pet to it's full advantage, letting it tank and deal damage for me. It's health is irrelivent for me, especially on blue mobs such as Drakes and Wyvrens of Cobalt Scar. Now, to me at 56, these drakes and wyvrens are mostly light blue, with a few dark blue here and there. My pet is equal or greater in level than these mobs, so can hold it's own with Burnout Haste and little more throughout the entire fight, negating the need to chain cast pets.<P>2) My equipment, much like a warrior or monk, is half of my advantage. Having located and purchased a Burnt Wood Staff (clickable Cinder Bolt, 333pt damage spell, 13.5 sec cast), I can nuke slow but easily without mana. Rarely, in my soloing in Cobalt Scar, do I waste mana for anything other than a pet and Burnout.<P>3) My Pre-50 Foci, with their instant click Reclaim Energy, come in very handy for both destroying my pet, AND returning to me some of the mana invested in my pet. On Wyvrens, this is about half (pet is at half health), on Drakes, it's lower, usually 20% of the pet's health. I can also get a 'reclaim' off any instant I need. Even if it weren't, I'm not using a lot of spell slots (Gate for emergencies, maybe sheielding if I'm feeling generous though it's not needed, pet (Air) and Burnout). I could have Reclaim Energy (the spell) memorized to do the same thing, and since I make sure the mob is running first (and will not come to attack me), the casting time is generally irrelivent.<P>Once the mob is on the run, I reclaim my pet to recover a portion of my mana cost, and finish the mob off with my Burnt Wood Staff. I can take as much time as I need to do that, and if I must, drop back and use Scars of Sigil to quickly finish the mob off. All told, my mana cost for using the equipment available to me as well as my spell set, is generally less than 20m per fight, and sometimes lower than that. I can, and have, maintained control over 5 seperate spawn points while still having time to med back a portion of that slow drain, get full experience, and such.<P>Now, supposing I were to use my pet "properly", to let it finish out the fight for me. If I wanted to gain full experience, I would have to nuke at least twice with Char, as my Burnt Wood Staff by itself does not put out damage fast enough to keep up with a 54 (average) hitting pet, hasted to 60%. I must make sure that I do half the damage before my pet does, so that I can be assured of gaining full experience for MY hard work. However, Thanks to all MY hard work, I now must med up the 30% of my mana that I wasted outdamaging my pet. With a drain of 30% mana per fight, I could do 3 fights at best before I must med up a full bar of mana. Or I could nuke a little, enough to help my pet live through the fight, and then wait for my pet to heal back up from 30-40health or lower to full, before confronting the next creature. However, thanks to the experience penalty, this light blue mob that I just fought just gave me almost no experience for my work.<P>I leave it to you which is more efficient and a smarter method to fighting. Reclaiming my pet, getting all my experience, and having little downtime and the capacity to control 5 spawn points. Letting my pet fight through, burning harder, getting all my experience, and being able to control 2-3 spawn points. Or Letting my pet fight through, burning lightly, getting only half my experience, and being able to control 2-3 spawn points at best. In my case, I prefer being able to fight more, get a greater reward, and use my skills to their optimum advantage.<P><B>As for groups, this is where it's less complicated.<P>If a pet is doing the most damage in a group, then there is an issue. If the group has a melee class, say a monk or a warrior (or even a rogue), and your pet is doing more damage than such a melee character, then that pet alone is of as much or more value to the group than any other member. Add to that a mage's casting power and you are looking at a single character providing more value to a group than any other single character could. If this happens a lot and if in a lot of groups the pet ends up outdamaging the melees, then I would begin to wonder that the class in question was overpowered, being able to deal out melee damage above those of actual melee classes as well as having spells.<P>If the pet is not outdamaging the melees of your group, then there is no problem here.</B><P>Agreed that if a melee is outdamaging your pet, then there is no problem. When it becomes a problem is when you group with someone who cannot outdamage your pet. You must reduce your capacity, restrain your pet, and control the ammount of damage done so that your group does not feel cheated out of experience. This point hits home very hard if an Epic Magician must fight alongside friends that are not epic'd or have no comperable gear. Yes, the Magician can tear through things, but in tearing through things, he is also leeching experience from the others for being so good at what he does. It is at this point I question whether or not an epic'd mage doing extremely well at dealing damage is any different than an epic'd rogue that can assassinate. You basically state that because a magician is using this NPC character to put forth their primary mode of damage, they should be penalized by fullfilling their role as a damage dealer to their best ability.<P><B>But if it is, then there is a serious balance issue. The thing that counters the power of that pet class in that case is the experience going to pets.<P>The only time that I see this as a legitimate issue for groups is when there is no melee class in the group at all. In that case it is the pet that really makes the group viable (unless they are doing something like an AoE group without a tank, in which case the pet won't be there anyway). So in that case I'm not sure that it's unfair to allow the pet to suck up the experience, it's replacing a melee and makes the group viable.</B><P>I'm not sure if you're making this statement because Magicians do not necessarily need melee classes around, or whether or not there's some lingering vision that states that the optimum group consists of at least one melee class, or what. Let me put it another way.<P>Magicians are, by looks, a melding of Melee and Wizardry. We deal damage in Melee through our companion, we deal damage through our spells. Neither a Magician pet, nor a Magician can stand alone, as each are very very weak compared to the whole. At higher levels, a Magican's pet is no warrior, it can, at best, tank only when there is significant peripheral damage to kill the mob before the mob kills the pet. That's it. Alone, against mobs that would give a high level Magician experience, a magician pet's lifespan is measured in seconds, as it's unlikely to remain alive longer than a minute.<P>The situation in which this pet experience leeching becomes very problematic is in pet only groups. By using the skills that have been granted to them, a group comprised entirely of Magicians can do as well a job killing things as any standard composition group. They do not do as well as any Area of Effect group. Yet this makeup of a group will suffer a penalty (I am unsure here whether or not it is meerly exps split 7 ways, 6 Magicians + highest damage pet, or 12 ways, as each pet will gain a share of the experience, assuming that no magician outdamages them). An AoE group will not suffer a penalty. Nor will a standard composition group. I have even heard of all Warrior groups in places like Velks, killing spiders nonstop, and requiring no more healing than could be provided by a 90hp breastplate heal. This group, too, will provide significant firepower and support to destroy anything in their path, yet they are not overshadowed by this loss of experience.<P>The worst aspect of this group pet leeching is not practically, but socially. Do you remember how much of a fuss was made about Hybrids leeching experience from groups because of their experience penalty? How well do you think Magicians are going to be recieved into standard pickup groups if there's this looming cloud of 'Don't do more damage than the tanks.' It's already hard enough to find a group as a Magician, this social stigma will have the same affect to Magicians as the Hybrid experience penalties had to hybrids. And not only that, but it all but requires a Magician restrain themselves at all times, to wait until half damage done to engage a pet, to find more reasons NOT to use a pet than to use one.<P><B>Ok, this is getting confusing. Let me try a different approach, see if it's any more comprehensible.<P>If pets are able to deal more damage and are more valuable than (or as valuable as) a melee class, then the experience cost is justified in all cases.</B><P>At post-50 levels, pets cannot absorb half as much damage as a standard melee can, due to lower level, lower AC, and lower stats. Pets in groups, moreso now than ever, are purely damage dealing creatures. They do not tank due to code-imposed restrictions.<P><B>If pets are doing less damage than the damage dealers in a group, then they won't be taking more than 1% (though it should probably just be 0%) and there is no issue</B><P><BR>Agreed. However, as above, the problem therein lies with why accept an Epic mage into your group, when his pet, uber damage dealer that he is, will KS the group a share of their experience?<P><B>If pets are less valuable than a melee and is in a group with no melee, then that group is using the pet to replace a melee character. In this case it might not be fair that the pet takes a share of the experience, but it might be.</B><P>Response to this below. I would argue, however, that in terms of a Magician only group, 6 pets == 1 warrior, 1 rogue, a healer, and 1 bard/enchanter (clarity affect). Reason being is that magicians generally have more mana when they have meleeing pets to dish out damage. On average 1 pet will have aggro and need healing, either by letting another pet tank and staying out of the fight, or by the expendature of Magician mana. The other pets count towards raw damage output, similar to a rogue. There is not a 1-1 correlation between 1 pet and 1 melee, and only in the presence of several pets do the tasks of tank and healer and damage dealer come into sight.<P><B>The classes that use pets in their soloing as the primary damage dealing tool are at least average or better soloers as things are now (with the possible exception of Beastlords, who I'm not real sure about right now). This would indicate that the penalty is fine as it is.</B><P>Being able to solo 'Average' is all well and good, but why penalize a class that can only solo 'average'? Why not penalize the class that can solo the best, or that can solo 4 mobs at once? How much sense does it make to punish a class because they do 'adequate' at soloing?<P>Note here that I will conceed that Magicians in certain circumstances can solo creatures that would otherwise be too dangerous, thanks to the Elementals and their natural high resistance to various kinds of magic. Cobalt Drakes and their Cold PBAoEs would tend to chew many melee classes alive, yet my single airpet that is immune (relatively) to cold based spells is never affected by it, and is never debuffed/dehasted by the anull magic affect within that AoE. These circumstances basically dictate casting mobs that use a single style of magic that we can tailor our pets assualt against to nullify some component of our enemy's offence.<P><B>The 'practice' vs 'design' thing is a valid issue, and is something that I'm not real fond of. But on its own isn't a reason ignore the arguments above.</B><P>I can see a logic behind the rationale for having the penalty. Basically, to make sense of the penalty, you have to have a certain mindset, and that is of a single class of two entities. Depending upon whether or not the subentity (the pet) does more work than the main entity (the player) determines whether or not the player was contributing anything at all, or whether or not the pet was doing all the work.<P>However, there is a problem to this mindset. It assumes that the main entity could exist acceptably without it's subentity. That a Magician could survive Norrath without their pet. In the case of Necromancers, this is probably true, that they can. A Necromancer has a wide range of defensive spells as well as an adequate pet for damage, and if caught without the pet, can generally survive well enough to evade, flee, or tend to the creature at hand. A Magician absolutely, positively cannot do enough damage, provide enough defense for themselves, or fend off even one enemy of comperable level (light blue or higher) without requiring some non-innate ability (Jboots for speed, Snare/Root off items). For Beastlords and Magicians both, classes that are heavily centered around their pets, you hold over them that they must keep up their end of the symbiosis or else they cannot gain rewards as good as a class without that dependance.<P>With the inflation of mob strength, required inflation of damage to bring these creatures down, and for beastlords and magicians, giving them the capacity to do more damage in the form of their key abilities is what it would seem to be about, in terms of Balancing PvE. As our pets become stronger and stronger (even visible as one levels a Magician), it becomes harder and harder to outdamage that pet. Compared against the Epic pet, a Magician must almost go full burn in order to outdamage that pet and 'hold up their end of the symbiosis' in order to reap full rewards.<P>I personally view (as mentioned above) that a Magician and their pet are a pair, inseperable, easily defeated seperately, but strong together. This is the same concept as a Rogue and his weapon, a Warrior and his armor, Melees and their weaponry, and other casters and their spells. Those classes rely upon those tools of their trade heavily, and recieve (now) no penalties for doing so. Magicians, using their trademark skills as Masters of Elementals, will be punished for using their skills without significant alternate contribution to said fights, almost doubling the required cost in bringing a creature down.<P>After all, with the current spell lineup that Magicians have, the ability to heal their pets or do damage, the ability to reclaim and make a new pet or tough it out with the current one they have, what benefit would a Magician recieve by choosing the 'deal damage through pet, heal pet as needed' strategy over the 'send pet and nuke' strategy? The former may keep the pet alive and win many a battle, but not ever doing any damage guarontees that particular Magician is only half as effective at gaining experience as the magician that selects the 'send pet and nuke' strategy. This particular experience penalty tends to force effectiveness towards a more 'full burn' state all the time rather than a 'make the best use of your spell set as you can'. <P>Though, I do have to add as an afterthought, if you think that a Magician can simply bring down an acceptable level of mob (moderate to high blue) without contributing their own damage, relying on their pet to do all of the work, I'd ask you to try playing a level 55 magician with a full compliment of spells, soloing just one skeleton in The Grey, or even against a comparable elemental in the Hole (Masters of Elementals and summonings). It's hard enough work as it is to do that, but to have this urgent need to make sure I outdamage my pet so that I can make sure I get all my experience is a burden that could be better left elsewhere, like fretting about what I'm going to do when a solitary add comes running my way to slaughter me while my one and only pet is otherwise occupied   <IMG SRC="smile.gif" border="0"><P><B>I'd be interested to hear discussion about those points (civil discussion&#8230;  <IMG SRC="wink.gif" border="0">. As I said, these are just my thought processes on this issue. I'm curious to see where I'm making errors, if any.</B><P>Personally, I'm pleased that you are receptive to comments, willing to express your thoughts on the matter, and call for discussion on topics that, at least on the surface, could raise one's frustrations with dealing with angry or sometimes irrational players. I'm hoping that we can present our thoughts on what we, the players, feel that our class is, what it is capable of, and what limitations overburden the class unnecessarily or are going to make our class less desirable by others in groups.<P>Rhasin Firestorm<BR>Conjurer of the 56th Season<BR>Prexus<BR><HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>--------------------<P>Rhasin Firestorm<BR>Conjurer of the 56th Season<BR>Prexus
