<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Man, some people get a certain streak of thought going, they can't break it.  Let's get back to the gist here by reviewing some items:<BR>A) Pets take one/100th of exp from a group in 99 percent of all instances.<BR>B) A mage is 60% wizard/60% tank, if you EVER do any breakdowns of log files<BR>C) Take a warrior, he kills a mob, no exp penalty. Take a mage, he kills a mob, 50% penalty. Kills another, and another- ok, the warrior is done sitting on his butt trying to regen, and can pull another mob.<BR>D)  This game doesn't end when you hit 60.  Verant makes money by keeping you interested in the game, trying new characters, taking your level 60 on harsh raids pitting your character (and you) against uber adversaries and generally having one hell of a good time... NOT by keeping you from making 60.  You will, regardless.<P>  Now, with a bit clearer perspective, I'd like to point out that I've played a mage to 55, and have my beastlord to 46.  Solo'd the mage frequently, solo'd the beastlord almost not at all.  By grouping, I've gotten the beastlord to level 46 in 17 days, and that's with quite a bit of farting around with quests in Shar Vahl thrown in for good measure... it's insanely easy to level a beastlord in a good group, least a Vah Shir.  Unlike a mage, a beastlord seems to be 75% hybrid melee/60% melee (pet)/25% shaman... it's ludicrous how utilitarian that class is.  Soloing a beastlord to me is easy, but still not as fast as a well-balanced, intelligent, experienced group of players (kudo's to my 'groupies' on the Luclin server  <IMG SRC="smile.gif" border="0"><BR>  The point of the above is to bring to light a feature of Everquest and it's design that I truly, truly love- disparity.  Diverseness.  I don't care WHAT class I have in my group.  I could care less whether I get healers/chanters/melee/hybrid/whatnot.. MORE than half the fun to me is to take a group of individuals, determine their strengths and make the group FLY!  Some of the best groups I've ever been with have been the most bizarre combination of classes imaginable, utilizing real flexibility and creativity to make the group just ROCK even though we had no 'chanter/cleric/snarer/meat shield/etc.'  They've been some of the most fun groups I've ever been in because they were a CHALLENGE!  Not a French dinner on a silver platter.  Not "I'll hit auto-attack while I watch this re-run of Baywatch and listen to Beastie Boys and talk to my homie on the phone".  A challenge that we met, overcame, excelled, and felt superior about after it was all said and done. An exceptional feeling, for just a video game  <IMG SRC="smile.gif" border="0">  So, everyone seems to like to concentrate on their weaknesses.  I like to concentrate on my strengths.  People like to complain about where they don't do well.  I like to boast about where I do well. If some of the posters had their way in my observation, I think they would have pets that could maul warriors, never die, be artificially intelligent, and loot the corpses for their casters, while the caster had the ability to cast wear plate, wield a sword, cast crack on themselves, regen, and nuke like a wizard... be (god I loathe this word...) 'uber' &gt;P  Enjoy.  Be a strong part of a team.  Display your strengths, overcome your weaknesses.  Cooperate, and succeed.  Excel.  Quit whining :P<P>  Arundayan Ironeye/Arunhakk Igatahayirbaal<BR>    55 Elementalist/46 Beastlord<BR>            Luclin server
