<HR size="1" color="#dedfdf">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
The post up there said that our pets are <P>"Doing as much damage as a melee class, and therefore as just as viable as one, and should get as much xp as they do."<P>(paraphrased)<P>Now whomever wrote this obviously has never played a pet class into high levels, or just isn't thinking straight...  I play a beastlord, and I can tell you that even if my pet did twice the damage as a monk, it would not be as viable to the group as a monk, here's why:<P>1.) until I get 27 or so levels into AA skills, we have no /pet hold command...  So if I'm getting attacked, or my pet is getting attacked, the pet attacks back, and there is no way to tell the pet to "back off" (even though there is a back off command) because he backs off for a second, and then once the mob attacks again, our pet is right back at it.  So there is no way to make our pet stop attacking so that an enchanter, or bard can mez...  which is crucial in high level encounters. (especially fighting mobs that cast AOE spells.)  An actual class however, say a monk, would definatly, and easily be able to not hit the attack button and let the enchanter mez.<P>2.) Pathing.  our pets will go every which way in a dungeon, training everything in it's path, where as a melee character would be able to follow more smartly. Pets would not be able to follow from the zone to the camp spot, normally you do not cast a pet until you have fought your way to where your gonna fight for a while. So that entire trip, the pet is not even up fighting, where as the real character would be.<P>3.) Taunt...   Being a beastlord, my pet not only taunts, but it also proc's an extra taunt, but he has *never* taken aggro off me, or a group member...  I do not believe pet taunts are working as designed...  My pet way outdamages me, and he taunts, and he procs taunt, but he still never takes aggro..  where as a warrior or an sk can definatly take aggro.<P>Here's the point I'm getting at...<P>All those things I listed are things that verant has said "Are the downfall to the pet class, every class has it's ups and downs"<P>So if that's the downfall, then the XP penalty is just kicking us while we're down? Here's my suggestion: Pick one!<P>I wouldn't mind the xp penalty at ALL if I could control my pet as well as a real characater controls his. And something to fix pathing (maybe a command that makes the pet stay exactly 2 clicks behind you at all times, no wandering, just bam locked in.)<P>OR...<P>Keep all the hard "downfalls" to playing a pet class in, and ditch the XP penalty.. <P>Bottom line is, None of us would mind giving our pets their equal share of the XP *if* they earned it, but just because they can sometimes dish out as much damage as a real melee character does *NOT* mean they are as viable to the group, and does not mean their doing the same share of work that a real one is doing, and therefore they do not deserve all that extra EXP.  <IMG SRC="smile.gif" border="0"><P>Thanks for taking the time to read this, I hope I made sense.<P>=Vadorn.
</FONT>
